  1. In this question, you will examine the chi-square and Students t distributions.
  • On the same graph, plot the probability curves of chi-squared distributed random variables with 1, 2, 5 and 10 degrees of freedom. Use different colors and line styles for each curve.
# Chi-square distribution
x.vals = seq(0, 15, length=100)

plot(x.vals, dchisq(x.vals, df=1), type="l", lwd=2, ylab="pdf", xlab="x",lty=1, col=1)
lines(x.vals, dchisq(x.vals, df=2), type="l", lwd=2, lty=2, col=2)
lines(x.vals, dchisq(x.vals, df=5), type="l", lwd=2, lty=3, col=3)
lines(x.vals, dchisq(x.vals, df=10), type="l", lwd=2, lty=4, col=4)
legend(x="topright", legend=paste("df=", c(1,2,5,10), sep=""), lty=1:4, col=1:4, lwd=2)
title("Chi-square Distribution")

  • On the same graph, plot the probability curves of Students t distributed random variables with 1, 2, 5 and 10 degrees of freedom. Also include the probability curve for the standard normal distribution. Use different colors and line styles for each curve.
# Students t distribution
x.vals = seq(-5, 5, length=100)
ub = max( c(dt(0, df=c(1,5,10,60)), dnorm(0)) )

plot(x.vals, dt(x.vals, df=1), type="l", lwd=2, ylim=c(0, ub), ylab="pdf", xlab="x",lty=1, col=1)
lines(x.vals, dt(x.vals, df=2), type="l", lwd=2, lty=2, col=2)
lines(x.vals, dt(x.vals, df=5), type="l", lwd=2, lty=3, col=3)
lines(x.vals, dt(x.vals, df=10), type="l", lwd=2, lty=4, col=4)
legend(x="topleft", legend=paste("df=", c(1,2,5,10), sep=""), lty=1:4, col=1:4, lwd=2)
title("Student's t Distribution")

  1. Consider a one month investment in two Northwest stocks: Amazon and Costco. Suppose you buy Amazon and Costco at the end of September at \(P_{A,t-1} = \$38.23, P_{C,t-1} = \$41.11\) and then sell at the end of the October for \(P_{A,t} = \$41.29, P_{C,t} = \$41.74\) . (Note: these are actual closing prices for 2004 taken from Yahoo!)

(a) What are the simple monthly returns for the two stocks? (b) What are the continuously compounded returns for the two stocks? (c) Suppose Costco paid a \(\$0.10\) per share cash dividend at the end of October. What is the monthly simple total return on Costco? What is the monthly dividend yield? (d) Suppose the monthly returns on Amazon and Costco from question (a) above are the same every month for 1 year. Compute the simple annual returns as well as the continuously compounded annual returns for the two stocks. (e) At the end of September, 2004, suppose you have \(\$10,000\) to invest in Amazon and Costco over the next month. If you invest \(\$8,000\) in Amazon and \(\$2,000\) in Costco, what are your portfolio shares, \(x_A \text{ and } x_C\). (Assume partial share purchases are possible) (f) Continuing with the previous question, compute the monthly simple return and the monthly continuously compounded return on the portfolio. Assume that Costco does not pay a dividend.

#  c1*uk1 = us1

  1. Let \(R_t\) denote the simple monthly return and assume that \(R_t \sim N(\mu, \sigma^2)\). Consider the 2-period simple return \(R_t(2) = (1 + R_t)(1 + R_{t-1}) - 1\).
# * (a) Assuming that $\mathrm{COV}(R_t, R_{t-1}) = 0$, show that $E[R_t R_{t-1}] = \mu^2$ .   Hint: Use $\mathrm{COV}(R_t, R_{t-1}) = E[R_t R_{t-1}] - E[R_t]E[R_{t-1}]$ 

#  COV(R_t,R_t-1) = 0 
#  COV(R_t,R_t-1) = E[R_tR_t1] E[Rt]E[R_t1] = 0
#  Therefore, E[R_tR_t1] = E[Rt]E[R_t1] = mu^2 

# * (b) Show that $E[R_t(2)] = (1 + \mu)^2 - 1$

#  E[Rt(2)] = E[(1 + Rt)(1 + R_t1) 1]
#           = E[Rt + R_t-1 + RtR_t-1]
#           = E[Rt] + E[R_t-1] + E[RtR_t-1]
#           = mu + mu + mu^2
#           = 2mu + mu^2 + 1 - 1
#           = (1 + mu)^2 - 1


# * (c) Is $R_t(2)$ normally distributed? Why or why not?

#  NO. Since E[Rt(2)] = (1 + mu)^2 - 1, which is not equal to mu, so R_t(2) is not normally    distributed.
